article.description:
Tina Thompson scored 17 points and Sheryl Swoopes
added 14 as Houston held off elimination from the WNBA
playoffs Sunday with a 69-48 victory over Sacramento.
article.headline: Comets lead throughout to even series
article.linkText: Comets rout Monarchs to force Game 3
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- The Houston Comets found a cure for their
late-season slump just in time to keep their season going.

Tina Thompson scored 17 points and Sheryl Swoopes added 14 as
the Comets held off elimination from the WNBA playoffs Sunday with
a 69-48 victory over the Sacramento Monarchs.

The victory tied the series at 1-1 with the deciding game
Tuesday night at Compaq Center.

"At times, I thought we were unstoppable," Swoopes said. "If
you'd told me it would be this kind of game, I wouldn't believe
you. I thought it was going to be more of a battle. Today, I can
honestly say that we wanted it more than they did."

The four-time WNBA champion Comets lost five of their last six
regular-season games, lost three straight for the first time in
team history and were beaten 65-59 in the playoff opener at
Sacramento.

"We knew it was do or die, and I told everybody before the game
that I don't want to go home," Swoopes said. "Tonight we came out
ready to play. We got our transition on early and think that was
the key today."

Leading 34-19 at the half, Swoopes fueled a 19-4 charge early in
the period that put the game out of reach. Thompson and Swoopes,
who had eight points in the second half, sat out the final 6:42
while backups finished the game.

Houston never trailed in Game 2, jumping to a 24-6 lead in the
opening minutes. Janeth Arcain led the Comets' first half charge.
She hit three straight baskets and Ukari Figgs followed with a
3-pointer to make it 17-4.

After a basket by Sacramento's Ticha Penicherio, Thompson hit a
layup, Swoopes followed with a basket and Thompson hit a 3-pointer
for the 24-6 lead, the Comets' biggest lead of the half.

Yolanda Griffith led the Monarchs with 20 points and 11
rebounds. Tangela Smith added 12 points and Edna Campbell had 10.
Arcain finished with 13 points for the Comets.

"Getting that first game at home was very important," Griffith
said. "We didn't have the home court advantage and now we're even.
Tina was really hot, it seemed almost like she hit some miracle
shots so now we're 1-1."

The Comets won the regular-season series 3-1 against Sacramento
including a 74-47 victory on Aug. 5 that was Houston's biggest
victory margin of the season.

"They were more aggressive defensively," Monarchs coach John
Whisenant said. "They've done that before and we've been able to
deal with it. Today, I couldn't yell our people into moving. It was
like we were moving in mud.

"We weren't impatient. We just weren't moving."

Michelle Snow, named the league's most improved player prior to
the game, had 11 rebounds and nine points.

"We knew we wanted to come out and push the ball and make them
worry about all of us," Snow said. "We've got five players that
can score at any time, any way."
